```julia
function timezone_bumper(dt::DateTime, bump::Integer = 3)
    if !(isa(dt, DateTime))
        throw(ArgumentError("Input must be a DateTime, not a $(typeof(dt))"))
    end
    return dt + Dates.Hour(bump)
end

# Test the function
using Test
@test timezone_bumper(DateTime(2023, 1, 1, 12)) == DateTime(2023, 1, 1, 15)
```

This function `timezone_bumper` takes a `DateTime` object and increases it by the specified number of hours, with a default of +3 hours. It is designed to work only with `DateTime` types. If you try to pass a `Date` type or any other type that isn't a `DateTime`, an `ArgumentError` is thrown.
